sentences: "God Bless the Soldier", written in 1890, was dedicated to the Grand Army of the Republic.
Born in Wrentham, Massachusetts, she was of Puritan ancestry, her ancestors on the father's side having settled in Massachusetts in 1635.
In 1877, she returned to Boston, where she made her home.

One of her popular achievements in the double role of composer and poet was, "God Bless the Soldier", written for the National Encampment in Boston in August, 1890, and dedicated to the Grand Army of the Republic.
In 1878, she was publicly invited by a number of Bostonians to repeat a lecture series consisting of "Nature's Music", "National Music, Hymns and Ballads", "The Influence of Music", and "Liszt."
Never married, Hawes died in 1926 in Boston.
